04593nam a22007215i 9780226500393DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20212017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017018048  a9780226500393  a(DE-B1597)568257  a(OCoLC)1233040470  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBF161b.J64 2017 4aBF161b.J64 2017 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a1282231 aJohnson, Mark, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmbodied Mind, Meaning, and Reason :bHow Our Bodies Give Rise to Understanding /cMark Johnson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction Bringing the Body to Mind -- tChapter 1 Cognitive Science and Dewey’s Theory of Mind, Thought, and Language -- tChapter 2 Cowboy Bill Rides Herd on the Range of Consciousness -- tChapter 3 We Are Live Creatures Embodiment, American Pragmatism, and the Cognitive Organism -- tChapter 4 The Meaning of the Body -- tChapter 5 The Philosophical Significance of Image Schemas -- tChapter 6 Action, Embodied Meaning, and Thought -- tChapter 7 Knowing through the Body -- tChapter 8 Embodied Realism and Truth Incarnate -- tChapter 9 Why the Body Matters -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMark Johnson is one of the great thinkers of our time on how the body shapes the mind. This book brings together a selection of essays from the past two decades that build a powerful argument that any scientifically and philosophically satisfactory view of mind and thought must ultimately explain how bodily perception and action give rise to cognition, meaning, language, action, and values. A brief account of Johnson’s own intellectual journey, through which we track some of the most important discoveries in the field over the past forty years, sets the stage. Subsequent chapters set out Johnson’s important role in embodied cognition theory, including his cofounding (with George Lakoff) of conceptual metaphor theory and, later, their theory of bodily structures and processes that underlie all meaning, conceptualization, and reasoning. A detailed account of how meaning arises from our physical engagement with our environments provides the basis for a nondualistic, nonreductive view of mind that he sees as most congruous with the latest cognitive science. A concluding section explores the implications of our embodiment for our understanding of knowledge, reason, and truth. The resulting book will be essential for all philosophers dealing with mind, thought, and language.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCognition. 0aConsciousness. 0aHuman body (Philosophy) 0aHuman body (Philosophy). 0aMeaning (Philosophy) 0aMeaning (Philosophy). 0aMind and body. 0aPhilosophy of mind. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  acognitive science.  aembodied cognition.  aembodiment.  aimage schemas.  aknowledge.  ameaning.  ametaphor.  apragmatist philosophy.  areason.  atruth.1 aJohnson, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRohrer, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226500393423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226500393/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles